abstracts.content:
Paper presents the study conducted in Mokotów district in Warsaw, encompassing circular practices of eight chosen local entities, from private, public and NGO sectors. The choice was based on the preliminary research showing that the entities were already engaged in some form of the circular transition. The definition of the circular economy applied in the study was based on the one proposed by Kircherr, Reike and Hekkert describing a circular economy as an economic system based on business models replacing the ‘end-of-life’ concept with reducing, alternatively reusing, recycling and recovering materials in production/distribution and consumption processes. The aim is to accomplish sustainable development, by creating environmental quality, economic prosperity and social equity, to the benefit of current and future generations. The goals of the study encompassed:
· verification if there is a common understanding of what circular economy is;
· identification and comparison of circular practices introduced by various actors;
· identification of existing incentives for the circular practices and expected benefits;
· pinpointing the obstacles and barriers, both within organizations and outside.
The identified practices were also verified to support more specific goals of circular economy, present in the literature. The findings shows that current benefits of circular transition are limited and the actions are mostly driven by personal involvement. Lack of the support of local administration is evident, as well as the limitation of the market solutions. Networking turns are to be one of the most important aspects of efficient circular practices.
